   722→directly from the typed `RestrictionInfo` objects instead of using the string-based Multimaps.
   723→
   724→### Additional Restriction Types
   725→
   726→If new OWL restriction types are needed in the future:
   727→
   728→1. Add new record to `RestrictionInfo` sealed interface
   729→2. Update `from()` factory method to handle new type
   730→3. Update `applyToArraySchema()`, `impliesRequired()`, `impliesArray()` as needed
   731→4. Compiler will identify all pattern matching switches that need updating
   732→
   733→## Lessons Learned
   734→
   735→### What Went Well
   736→
   737→- Sealed interfaces provide excellent type safety for discriminated unions
   738→- Pattern matching eliminates entire classes of bugs
   739→- Incremental refactoring (dual-writing during transition) worked well
   740→- Test-driven approach caught issues early
   741→
   742→### Challenges
   743→
   744→- Java 21 doesn't support unnamed patterns (`_`), had to use named variables
   745→- Some complexity in `DataPropertyMapper` due to boolean combinations
   746→- Had to maintain backward compatibility with string-based range storage
   747→
   748→### Best Practices Applied
   749→
   750→- Small, focused changes
   751→- Comprehensive testing after each phase
   752→- Preserved existing functionality while improving internals
   753→- Used modern Java features (records, sealed interfaces, pattern matching)
